        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>[Down]</placeName>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>P.S. I begin to think it would be far safer to measure pollen <hi rend="doubleUnderline">dry</hi> . Some time try whether you could not put thin glass over dry scattered pollen &amp; secure thin glass over the slide by 2 little balls of wax as big as pin’s heads.— You must be tired of my requests, otherwise I would send another red Cowslip to be measured dry.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> The Pulmonaria pollen looks very different size dry.— Look for the shrivelled &amp; small grain in long-styled Pulmonaria in <hi rend="doubleUnderline">dry</hi> state.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 <hi rend="bold">dry</hi>] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘quit’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.2 scattered] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">1.5 Look] ‘L’ <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘l’</note>
                </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the reference to observing shrivelled and small grains of <hi rend="italic">Pulmonaria angustifolia</hi> pollen, as CD had mentioned in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4495.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of 14 May [1864]</ref>; William responded to CD’s request to observe the pollen dry in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4500.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of 18 May [1864]</ref>. See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4442.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from H. E. Darwin to W. E. Darwin, [18 May 1864]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">William had already sketched pollen for CD from the two forms of wild yellow cowslip and from an equal-styled red cowslip (see memorandum from W. E. Darwin, [30 April 1864] and nn. 3 and 4). In his letters to W. E. Darwin of <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4480.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">3 May [1864]</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4483.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">5 May [1864]</ref>, CD had asked William to soak the yellow cowslip pollen the longest before measuring it; he included an equal-styled red flower from a new seedling in the second letter.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">For CD’s interest in the shrivelled pollen-grains from long-styled <hi rend="italic">Pulmonaria</hi> flower-buds, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4495.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to W. E. Darwin, 14 May [1864]</ref> and n. 6).</note>
        </div>        
            
